%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] # Black Start of Offshore Wind Farm and HVDC System
%[text] This project demonstrates the process of black starting a power network using offshore wind farm connected via VSC-HVDC. 
%[text] The VSC-HVDC links provides a controllable path to transfer black-start power from offshore wind farms to onshore areas, even when the onshore grid is completely de-energized.
%[text]{"align":"center"} ![](text:image:3e65)
%[text] ## Project Overview
%[text] - Demonstrates how grid-forming wind turbines can independently energize a dead offshore AC network and establish stable voltage and frequency.
%[text] - Shows the complete HVDC black-start sequence, including DC-link pre-charge, offshore voltage control, and onshore VSC grid-forming operation.
%[text] - Automated analysis framework developed using the `BlackstartAnalyzer` class for extraction of physically meaningful indices. \
%[text] ## Motivation
%[text] **Black start** is the capability of a generating unit or grid asset to start up without receiving external power supply and to energize part of the network, eventually allowing the restoration of the wider power system after a complete or partial blackout.
%[text] - Modern power systems are experiencing high penetration of inverter-based resources (IBRs), which reduces system inertia and makes grids more vulnerable to large disturbances.
%[text] - Traditional black-start units (diesel, coal, gas turbines) are being retired, creating a gap in system restoration capability.
%[text] - Offshore wind farms, equipped with grid-forming (GFM) control, can independently establish voltage and frequency on a dead network.
%[text] - Combining GFM wind turbines and HVDC technology creates a fast, and reliable black-start solution that supports system resilience in high-renewable power systems. \
%[text] ## System Overview 
%[text] This figure shows the unit test model which contains an offshore wind farm connected to the onshore AC grid through a $\\pm \\;320\\;\\textrm{kV}${"editStyle":"visual"} VSC-HVDC network. 
%[text] ![](text:image:42f8)
%[text] The VSC-HVDC network consists of onshore and offshore HVDC stations connected through 85 km long bipolar HVDC cables. 
%[text] ###  **Offshore Side Description:**
%[text] - The wind turbines generators (WTGs) connect to the offshore wind farm using fully-rated back-to-back converters.
%[text] - The wind farm has an installed capacity of  320 MW, where each wind turbine can generate a rated power of 18 MW at a wind speed of 11 m/s
%[text] - The offshore converter is grid-following which enables DC-voltage control on the HVDC link.
%[text] - Multiple Grid-Forming (GFM) wind turbine converters on the offshore site
%[text] - Remaining wind turbines as Grid-Following (GFL) converters \
%[text] As the  offshore HVDC station is in Grid-Following mode. This means it cannot self-generate the AC voltage reference to energize the offshore collection grid. 
%[text] Therefore, a subset of the WTGs  must operate in GFM mode initially to form the island. Once the offshore AC bus is live and stable, the offshore GFL WTGs can then lock its PLL and start delivering power.
%[text] ###  **Onshore Side Description:**
%[text] - Onshore AC island black-start (no main grid)
%[text] - Onshore VSC ($VSC\_{on}$): connects DC link to onshore AC bus
%[text] - The onshore VSC is grid-forming with droop control on voltage and frequency. \
%[text] ###  **CONTROL ROLES**
%[text] -   Power Synchronization Control (PSC)-based GFM WTs: form offshore AC grid and provide V/f support
%[text] -   GFL WTs: follow offshore grid and inject P/Q (MPPT or setpoint)
%[text] -   The off-shore converter station performs DC-voltage control, $VSC\_{off}$: Vdc-controlled (export power)
%[text] -   The on-shore converter station is a GFM controlled converter station,$VSC\_{on}$: GFM control, which performs the black start on the on-shore side. \
%[text] ###  **Control of Wind Turbine Converter**
%[text] 
%[text] ![](text:image:7894) ![](text:image:6467)
%[text] ## Black Start Sequence
%[text] You can execute the black-start sequence in a structured manner, beginning with DC-link charging through a pre-insertion resistor (PIR), followed by activation of DC voltage control at the offshore converter, and culminating in onshore grid formation using a GFM-controlled VSC. The coordinated interaction between offshore GFM wind turbines, the grid-following (GFL) HVDC converter, and the onshore GFM converter ensured stable voltage and frequency throughout the restoration process.
%[text] This figure shows the flowchart for the sequence of steps followed in the black-start process.
%[text] ![](text:image:6556)
%[text] \*\* In practice these steps are followed after  an auxiliary UPS is confirmed to be online, and provides power to all MMC gate drives, sensors, contactors, and SCADA system.\*\*
%[text] ### Charging the HVDC Offshore station and Cables using  Pre-insertion Resistor (PIR)
%[text] Once the offshore AC bus is live and stable, the offshore VSC (GFL) can then lock its PLL and begin DC-side charging through the pre-insertion resistor (PIR). The PIR on the AC side simultaneously protects the GFM WTG island from transformer inrush and limits the rectified DC charging current. During charging the VSC is blocked (diode-only path) for rectifying the AC voltage. The onshore is VSC is blocked during this stage.
%[text] The offshore VSC operates in two distinct phases during black start, separated by the DC voltage threshold ($V\_{\\mathrm{th}}${"editStyle":"visual"}):
%[text] **Phase 1** — Blocked (passive rectifier) when $V\_{\\mathrm{th}}${"editStyle":"visual"}\< 0.98\* $V\_{{\\mathrm{DC}}\_{\\mathrm{ref}} }${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] - All IGBT gate signals suppressed
%[text] - Freewheeling diodes conduct naturally
%[text] - Behaves as a 3-phase uncontrolled bridge rectifier
%[text] - DC output tracks: V\_dc → V\_dc,ref (clamped by onshore SM caps)
%[text] - No current control, no PLL active
%[text] - Duration: from PIR closure until V\_dc ≥ 0.98·V\_dc,ref \
%[text] **Phase 2** — GFL $V\_{\\mathrm{DC}} \\;${"editStyle":"visual"}control when $V\_{\\mathrm{th}}${"editStyle":"visual"}\> 0.98\* $V\_{{\\mathrm{DC}}\_{\\mathrm{ref}} }${"editStyle":"visual"} 
%[text] - Modulation enabled, PLL locks (|$V\_{\\mathrm{AC}}${"editStyle":"visual"}| already near rated)
%[text] - Outer loop regulates DC bus voltage
%[text] - D-axis current reference is the output of Dc voltage PI controller
%[text] - Q-axis current reference is based on reactive setpoint \
%[text] ### Starting the Onshore Converter Station and Network Energization
%[text] The onshore VSC operates in grid-forming mode and is responsible for establishing the onshore 200 kV AC network. This GFM black start is performed where the DC input power comes from the HVDC cable already charged to full voltage by the time the onshore VSC begins AC energization. 
%[text] #### Onshore Energization Sequence
%[text] - The MCC submodule capacitors are pre-charged from the DC bus already at rated voltage  from cable charging, no separate pre-charging needed.
%[text] - GFM voltage reference begins ramping: V\_ref: 0 → 1.0 pu at 0.5 pu/s.
%[text] - Onshore transformer HV breaker closes, transformer is energized  and GFM manages inrush via controlled voltage ram.
%[text] - Once onshore bus voltage is stable, the load feeder breakers closes.
%[text] - Load connection is a step disturbance which is managed by GFM by gradually load pickup using a controlled ramp on the GFM power reference. \
%%
%[text] ## Results and Automated Analysis
%[text] In this study, the pre-insertion resistor (PIR) is set to 0.15 Ω. The PIR is inserted during the DC-link charging phase to limit inrush current and protect converter components. It remains active for a finite duration and is subsequently bypassed.
%[text] Specifically, the PIR is active during the time interval:  $t=\\;9\\;s\\;${"editStyle":"visual"} to $t=15\\;s${"editStyle":"visual"}.
%[text] ### **Load Simulation Results**
%[text] Ensure that the simulation has been executed and results are available in the workspace.
model = 'VSCHVDCunitblackstart';
if exist('blackstartResults','var') ~= 1  %[output:group:6f887146]
    disp('Run Simulink model first to generate blackstartResults')  %[output:13c2bb49]
    load_system(model);
    in0 = Simulink.SimulationInput(model); % create simulink simulation input
    in0 = in0.setModelParameter('SimulationMode','accelerator'); % set model parameters
    blackstartResults = sim(in0); % run simulation
end %[output:group:6f887146]
%%
%[text] **Initialize Analyzer**
%[text] The `BlackstartAnalyzer` class processes the `logsout` data, extracts key signals, detects events, and computes performance indices.
analyzer = BlackstartAnalyzer(blackstartResults.logsout);
%%
%[text] ### **Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)**
%[text] The KPIs quantify the performance of the black-start sequence across DC charging, control transition, and grid formation phases.
KPI = analyzer.KPITable;
disp(KPI) %[output:97e63780]
%[text] **Interpretation of KPIs**
%[text] - DC Rise Time: Indicates how quickly the HVDC link is energized
%[text] - DC Overshoot: Reflects aggressiveness of DC control
%[text] - Voltage Build Time: Measures effectiveness of offshore grid formation
%[text] - Frequency Deviation: Indicates system stability
%[text] - Power Mismatch: Captures transient energy imbalance
%[text] - Total Black-start Time: Overall restoration duration \
%[text] ### Black-start Dynamic Response
%[text] The dashboard provides a consolidated view of key signals including: DC voltage, offshore and onshore voltages, frequency response, power transfer.
analyzer.plotDashboard(); %[output:915b86fc]
%[text] **Observations**
%[text] - Offshore voltage leads the energization process
%[text] - Onshore voltage follows controlled ramping behavior
%[text] - Frequency deviations occur during load pickup
%[text] - Power mismatch highlights transient energy exchange in the DC link
%[text] - The analyzer automatically detects key black-start events: DC charging start, DC voltage ready, offshore grid readiness, onshore energization, load connection.  \
%%
%[text] ## Parametric Study Using PIR Sweep
%[text] This section evaluates the effect of the pre-insertion resistor (PIR) using parallel simulations with `parsim`. 
%[text]  the PIR is active during the time interval:  $t=\\;9\\;s\\;${"editStyle":"visual"} to $t=15\\;s${"editStyle":"visual"}.
%[text] This significantly improves computational efficiency when running multiple scenarios.
%[text] ### Define PIR Values
pIRValues = [0.15 0.25 0.5 1]; nCases = numel(pIRValues);
%[text] ### Create Simulation-Input Array
%[text] Simulink simulation input
set_param(model,'FastRestart','off'); % Set model in fast-restart mode
for k = 1:nCases
    in(k) = Simulink.SimulationInput(model);
    in(k) = in(k).setVariable('rpir', pIRValues(k));
    in(k) = in(k).setModelParameter('SimulationMode','accelerator');
end

% Run parallel simulations
resultsParameterSweep = parsim(in,'ShowProgress','off'); %[output:352af9fe]
set_param(model,'FastRestart','off');
%%
%[text] ### Analyze Results for PIR Sweep
results = struct(); 
for k = 1:nCases 
    analyzer = BlackstartAnalyzer(resultsParameterSweep(k).logsout); 
    results(k).pIR = pIRValues(k); 
    results(k).KPI = analyzer.KPI; 
    results(k).signals = analyzer.signals; 
    results(k).event   = analyzer.event;
end
%[text] #### Time-Domain Comparison: Effect of PIR
%[text] This section compares the dynamic response of key variables across different PIR values.
%% Plots for time domain comparison
figure('Name','PIR Comparison Dashboard','Units','normalized','OuterPosition',[0 0 0.5 0.5])  %[output:3a6e9f54]
tlo = tiledlayout(3,1,'TileSpacing','compact','Padding','compact');  %[output:3a6e9f54]
%% ================= OFFSHORE VOLTAGE ================= 
nexttile  %[output:3a6e9f54]
hold on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
for k = 1:nCases 
sig = results(k).signals; 
plot(sig.V_off.time,sig.V_off.value,'LineWidth',1.5) %[output:3a6e9f54]
end 
title('Offshore Voltage Magnitude','FontWeight','bold')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
pir_vals = [results.pIR];
legendStrings = arrayfun(@(x) sprintf('PIR=%.2f', x), pir_vals, 'UniformOutput', false);
lgd = legend(legendStrings); %[output:3a6e9f54]
ylabel('Voltage (pu)')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
xlim([2 20]) %[output:3a6e9f54]
grid on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
box on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
%% ================= DC VOLTAGE ================= 
nexttile  %[output:3a6e9f54]
hold on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
for k = 1:nCases 
    sig = results(k).signals; 
    plot(sig.Vdc.time,sig.Vdc.value,'LineWidth',1.5)  %[output:3a6e9f54]
end 
title('DC Voltage','FontWeight','bold')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
ylabel('Vdc') %[output:3a6e9f54]
xlim([2 20]) %[output:3a6e9f54]
grid on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
box on %[output:3a6e9f54]
%% ================= OFFSHORE POWER ================= 
nexttile  %[output:3a6e9f54]
hold on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
for k = 1:nCases 
    sig = results(k).signals; 
    plot(sig.P_off.time,sig.P_off.value,'LineWidth',1.5)  %[output:3a6e9f54]
end 
title('Offshore Power','FontWeight','bold')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
ylabel('Power')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
xlabel('Time (s)')  %[output:3a6e9f54]
grid on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
box on  %[output:3a6e9f54]
xlim([2 20]) %[output:3a6e9f54]
title(tlo,'Time-Domain Comparison for PIR Sweep','FontWeight','bold') %[output:3a6e9f54]
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_8e74] This figure compares offshore voltage, DC voltage, and offshore power.
%[text] #### Comparative Analysis of PIR Impact
%[text] This section compares the effect of PIR values on voltage, frequency, and charging performance.
%[text] **KPI Comparison Table**
%%
T = KPIComparison(results); %[output:7510877f]
%[text] **Voltage Dip vs PIR**
figure  %[output:479258ef]
plot(T.PIR, T.VoltageDip,'-o','LineWidth',1.8)  %[output:479258ef]
xlabel('PIR Value')  %[output:479258ef]
ylabel('Minimum Voltage (pu)')  %[output:479258ef]
title('Voltage Dip vs PIR')  %[output:479258ef]
grid on %[output:479258ef]
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_9437] **Frequency Dip vs PIR**
figure  %[output:7ebc0796]
plot(T.PIR, T.FreqDip,'-o','LineWidth',1.8)  %[output:7ebc0796]
xlabel('PIR Value')  %[output:7ebc0796]
ylabel('Minimum Frequency (Hz)')  %[output:7ebc0796]
title('Frequency Dip vs PIR')  %[output:7ebc0796]
grid on %[output:7ebc0796]
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_9961] **Charging Time vs PIR**
figure  %[output:003ab623]
plot(T.PIR, T.ChargingTime,'-o','LineWidth',1.8)  %[output:003ab623]
xlabel('PIR Value')  %[output:003ab623]
ylabel('Charging Time (s)')  %[output:003ab623]
title('Charging Time vs PIR')  %[output:003ab623]
grid on %[output:003ab623]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Key Observations
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | **Low PIR** | **Medium PIR**  | **High PIR**  |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Fast charging | Balanced performance | Smooth voltage and frequency |
%[text] | Higher voltage and frequency disturbances | Moderate charging time | Slow charging |
%[text] | More aggressive system behavior | Controlled voltage/frequency response | Reduced stress on system |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] The PIR introduces a trade-off between:
%[text] ⚡ Speed (charging time)
%[text] - Lower PIR values lead to faster DC charging but introduce stronger transients \
%[text]  ⚡Stability (voltage & frequency dips)
%[text] - Higher PIR values smooth the response but increase energization time
%[text] - Voltage and frequency dips increase with aggressive charging (low PIR)
%[text] - An optimal PIR balances speed and stability \
%[text] ## Conclusion
%[text] This study demonstrates the feasibility and effectiveness of black-starting an offshore wind farm integrated with a VSC-HVDC system using grid-forming (GFM) control. The results confirm that offshore wind turbines, when operated in GFM mode, can successfully establish an AC voltage reference, enabling the energization of the offshore network and subsequent charging of the HVDC link without support from an external grid. The automated analysis framework developed using the `BlackstartAnalyzer` class enabled systematic extraction of key signals, event detection, and computation of physically meaningful KPIs.

